segments.text: Okay, now we got it.
It's, what, Tuesday, April 15th.
Tax day.
Tax day.
1997, and we're at the home of Joe and Betty Moore in Austin, Texas, and we're going to talk about the Texas A&M University Press and about the Moores.
And I don't know who wants to begin, but...
No, you were starting out.
Tell me about how you came along, literally, originally.
How I got to A&M.
You were born in Alvin.
Let's start there.
That's correct.
And my dad was a dairy farmer.
He actually had four dairies.
So I was raised on a farm until I went to A&M.
Okay, now when were you born, if you don't mind?
March 29th.
And in our family, we had four boys and three girls.
Seven.
Our older brother went to the M. Actually, he went to the junior college first, and he went to the M.
Did you go to school in Alvin?
Oh yes, I graduated in Alvin High School.
I think there were only twenty-four graduating seniors when I graduated in 1934.
But anyhow, I guess the first I heard of A&M was my brother.
I suppose he liked it.
Then he decided my mother
said that she was going to have all of her children go to college.
So, Warren picked me up there one time.
I was divided between studying agriculture or engineering.
I got interested in engineering because the oil exploration was active.
about that time in the area where we lived.
Actually, we brought in a field several miles from where we lived.
There was a lot of geophysical activity going on.
That's where I got interested in oil business.
I didn't know whether to stay in agriculture, which I knew from the ground up already.
Too well.
My dad encouraged me to
studied engineering.
Actually, I started from geology.
And they had what they called a course in geological engineering at that time, and that's what I enrolled in.
Okay, so what year was that?
I started in 1934.
Yeah.
And was Buck Shewitz in that class?
No, he was much younger than me.
Okay.
I'd say I was in class of 1938.
All right.
I'd say he was about forty.
Forty-one.
Okay.
And who, when you were enrolled, I just finished doing a little history of chemical engineering at A&M, and Duke Fortin was one of the big
chemical engineer, I guess he's kind of, what all are you doing?
Did you remember him at all?
Was he at EMF?
Yes, sir.
As a professor.
The only one I remember is Brake.
Okay, yeah.
Professor Brake.
D-R-A-Y-T-O-R-E. Yeah.
Let's see, who was the head of EMF?
I was advised by people in agriculture that I've never passed chemistry or calculus.
Yeah, I did.
I changed from geological engineering to petroleum engineering because I was advised at that time it was easier to get a job.
But anyhow, I graduated petroleum engineering and then I decided that I needed more geology, more petroleum geology.
The professor at A&M at that time was what you call a hard rock geologist.
And he didn't know much about the, that was Dr. Baker, but anyhow.
Then I went to Oklahoma University and took all of their geology courses.
And I got a massive degree from there and I was lucky enough to have
offered us three jobs when I got out, probably because I had experience in the oil field.
Had you worked in the oil fields in the summer?
Yes.
I worked three summers on the drilling board.
One of my students.
During the, after I graduated,
And I was waiting to go to Oklahoma.
And I met Betty.
Betty was visiting her grandmother and uncle in Alvin.
She had been born in Alvin, but had moved to Ohio.
And she was visiting back when I met her.
I worked with her that summer when I was working in the rig and decided to get married.
So we married at Christmas time, actually December 23rd, when I was at Oklahoma University.
She was a big help with me all the time.
We were, I'd say, moving from job to job.
I first went with Cheryl, and we moved about ten times the first year.
It was actually a two-year transport.
And we moved, we lived in Louisiana.
We first went to
And then they moved me to Louisiana, worked on different things.
But the fact that I had worked in the oil field, I had quite an advantage over the other guys that had never been in the oil field.
And then having Betty along, it's more...
Anyhow, we were actually pretty privileged and moved up pretty fast.
In Shell.
How long were you with Shell?
About four years.
Four years.
And I had an offer with a smaller company
I had made up my mind that Shell had what they called exploitation engineering, not geology.
I wanted to get into geology, and I was offered a job in .
Anyhow, I took the job.
about twice the scale of Shell.
And I worked with them for about four years.
And then there was a consultant, I'd say, an independent geologist that had found the field and was working with Fuller for a long time.
a fellow named Sam Marshall.
He was probably one of the best site geologists.
He got no publicity because he didn't publish anything or anything else.
He just found quite a lot of oil.
His dad, he was a graduate of the University of... No, no, no.
His dad, he may be right.
He could have been a graduate.
professor, head of geology department at Madison, Wisconsin.
Anyhow, that was the background.
He knew more basic limestone geology, and that's what West Texas is.
And I went independent working under him.
So I've been in independent geology since.
So what year, what year did you go independent, just out of curiosity?
I'd say, let's see, I started working in the 40s or 50s.
In the 50s or 50s.
In Hobbs, New Mexico.
Right.
And we lived in Hobbs, New Mexico for about a year.
Oh, did you?
Okay.
Because that was the development of the deeper zones in the Western Basin.
Right.
And because of our interest in
production, re-production, gathered sands right down on the coast.
We got interested in the Williston Basin.
You know where the Williston Basin is in North Dakota?
Roughly, yeah.
So we would work during the winter months in West Texas and then the summer months in North Dakota.
You were migrants early on.
Well, actually, it's foresightedness that Sam Marshall had.
Actually, we were drawn to the area, the Wilson Basin, when a well blew out in Alberta County.
It was a big field that was a barnstorming reef, and we were trying to trace that reef down into the Wilson Basin.
We found out it was completely different geology, but we got interested and did work in the Western Basin before they found the field.
that we already had the geology and had made some ideas about where we had the best prospects.
We still, right now, my son is running our company.
He's got a little bit of a family on him.
Our office is in Midland.
In Midland.
We moved.
We advanced up from Oz to Midland.
To Midland, okay.
We're probably with Midland in the 60s.
And I've been retired all this time continually working.
Yeah, that's what happens.
My son Ron is our company now.
Our operation right now mostly is in the district.
Do you still keep up with him?
Not too much.
Well, he's getting faxed well reports every morning.
Yeah, we're still at it.
We had something going on in Louisiana.
But my son does, I mean he runs everything, the details.
And the only thing I do is try to help him with the archaeology.
That's interesting.
I know what you're talking about a little bit.
I worked with a seismograph team one summer
You really know something, man.

I did a fun book on, I don't know if you ever saw it, but I did a fun book on, I don't know if you ever saw it, but I did a fun book on, I don't know if you ever saw it, but I did a fun book on, I don't know if you ever saw it, but I did a
I know another thing about the oil business.
When they were having the big oil boom at College Station, I invested.
And I never saw $3,500 go down quite so fast in all my life.
That's the worst anything anybody can do is invest, but not in the oil business.
Oh, I tell you, it was interesting, educational.
Let Manny tell you a little bit about that.
Please, yeah.
early deals, because that kind of gets us up to where we started.
Actually, we were living in Midland.
No, I'm sorry.
We had moved to Midland and had a house out here at Lakeland.
And that's the time that we got involved with Frank Wardle, even though we had been involved
with the Farmer Students Association and knew Jack Williams before that time.
Okay, well, we'll come back there.
Betty, you're from Alvin, too?
I'm from Alvin, but I moved to Ohio when I was 12 and stayed there.
Did you really?
Well, it's just like you said, people that have never been on an airplane and they don't know what they've been taught in their backyard or something.
Where'd you move to in Ohio?
It was Deshner, Ohio.
Northwest Ohio.
Anyway, as soon as I could, I got back to Texas.
But anyway, I met Joe and Alvin.
I didn't know him.
I thought he was going to A&M.
I met him later through a mutual girlfriend.
He didn't know that he was married.
That happens.
She's on the good side of it.
Well, we married in 1939, and we had three sons.
When we first got married, we moved about four or five years ago.
We moved 10 times in the first two years.
It was a little bit of a shell.
It was a training program, you know, so we'd be one office.
We started out in Houston.
That should have been a good background, too.
Did you have a good sense of the whole thing?
I knew what they were doing.
I worked in a gasoline bank.
I worked at a rig.
And then I worked in an office.
I worked under a law department.
I had a cousin who retired from, Bob Jordan.
He was living in Thailand.
What area was he in?
So then you got together, you married, you moved a lot, and how was the oil business for you?
Well, we liked every place we lived.
We lived in some dumps.
Top salary for a guy with a master's degree in geology at that time was $135 a month.
With three owners I had.
Two of them were 125, and one of them was 135.
Because I took shells in the training camp.
I remember another thing about the oil business.
When I finished Texas in 1956, I had a lot of friends in geology.
They didn't get any jobs.
They were a shock.
And so
When did you begin to feel like you were settling down a little bit?
When we went to Hobbs and Joe decided to leave and go independent, then we pretty much did what we did.
Yeah, we bought a house and we pretty much settled down.
Now, as an independent consultant geologist type in those days, was that kind of a boom and bust business?
Well, it depends on how you did it.
Actually, we saw...
fluctuations in the price of oil and the activity, but we were never busted.
Yeah, that's true.
We pretty much had a gradual increase in
Well, I'd say that basically, if you look at the long-range planning, the ups and downs, they are a foolish thing, just like the stock market, but we would never call it that.
During those years, how about A&M?
When did you begin to get loose into the A&M?
Well, I, in the earlier days, well, I say not the earlier days, I say the middle.
I got to hear too much about A&M.
As a result, we only had one son go to school there.
And I don't know if it's because they, you know, hurt so much of it.
Yeah.
Were you active in A&M activity?
I guess there were a lot of Aggies with you in the business, probably.
Well, yes.
Actually, in living, I had four classmates that lived there at the time.
Three of us were in .
When we got started with A&M, I suppose I actually started it because the Southwest
We started A&M Club as a lot of clubs started by having a muster.
We had a muster of our house.
Oh, okay.
Is that right?
And we invited some of the A&M people that we knew.
Was that in Hobbs?
Yes.
And that club that we started, there was a couple other Aggies living there.
My favorite, he's still there.
But anyhow, we would have a muster up there every year, and then I got involved in the association.
I was in what they called the best Texas representative assembly at that time, and then finally got appointed to the assembly.
Well, the president elected first, and then the president, then the pastor.
And then he was on the Development Foundation seven years.
Well, I began to learn to like it.
After a while.
Let's say you couldn't help but like it.
Well, Joe was a charter member of the 12th man, you know, with that thing.
It was so small, maybe we could meet over in the kitchen.
Yeah.
We saw both, at that time, the former Student Association and the Haggard Club, we saw them develop and improve almost every year.
And right now, they're just 100,000 percent better than they used to start there, because they make improvements every year.
It's really impressive, you know, the non-exemption student student out there.
Who do you attribute mostly?
Is it any single person, or the former students, or to that kind of organization development of that association?
Those are unique associations.
Actually, they started improving the association at the time that the Aggie jokes were being told, and it was affecting the
students coming in, and I'd say that Bob Latimer was present at that time, and they made an effort to send the students out to the high schools and so forth.
They started selling the program.
You see, the whole thing
The difference in the early days on the Student Association was they used to have meetings, and they called them BB meetings, Beer and Blame.
And a lot of them, let's say Jim Sewell would come to the early ones, and later Jim Harvey Cash.
And they thought only of improving the association to help the image of A&M.
And they started improving the, what do you call it, the text society, the magazine.
I've been in a lot of complaints about it, really.
And I guess Jerry Cooper came in about that time, too, right?
That's right.
I'm always admiring Buck Wirons, too.
Yes.
They actually, about the time, in the early days, they kind of started working on the fundraiser.
and having programs.
The first program was probably the fundraiser, but they started going into other programs to improve the image and combat the bad Aggie jokes.
For a while, they actually affected the senior partners in high school.
But anyhow, then for some reason later on,
A&M got real popular for seniors to come to.
And all the programs that Jack Williams probably had more to do with telling students what to tell.
Let's talk about, I guess, that time period now when the A&M Press is getting ready to get started.
What is your, I guess, let's see, I'm not sure where to start it and you can bring things in, but what is your first recollection
I'm hearing about him technically in the American press.
Yes.
Yes.
I think that at that time, this would have been 74, and I had been president of the association in 72.
Okay.
I'm not sure of those dates.
I'll check it.
I know that I was president in 1974.
because at that time they started having models.
I remember that Bob Latimer said we're going to get better every year.
Just before me, Melvin Moss, he had a slogan of
a better communication between the students and alumni and administration.
My field was more dull in 74.
I remember I was in 74.
But anyhow, all of the programs at that time started improving
and getting, actually we were getting to get the better quality of people coming in, instead of just the rah-rah.
We used to go in the rah-rah sock booth.
We've been out there 15 years, I can't say that.
Anyhow, the first time that we saw Frank Wardle, he and Jack and several others,
I asked them, I don't know whether it was Bob Walker or Randy Mattson.
They flew out to Amarillo to talk with Harold Dunn.
You know Harold Dunn?
Yeah, I know.
In fact, there's a letter in the files about the same time.
And they, French, had been aware of a young artist
that lived in Sweetwater, and had made some paintings of West Texas ranches and so forth, and this fellow in Fort Worth had told Frank about this fellow at one of the museums.
But anyhow, they flew out there and made the pitch to Harold Dunn

to put up some money for the book series and harold at that time said that he was kind of closing out his estate or something and they were flying back from amarillo and they said let's stop by and see joe moore and we just happened
to be there, we actually were staying in two motel rooms.
We had two motel rooms side to side.
And we, at that time, we had built a house at Lakewood.
We built a house there in 72.
Out here on the lake.
For some reason, we were back in Midland, so they got in touch with us.
I don't know exactly how, but they decided to stop by and talk to us.
And I can remember that we were in the hotel room there.
We were all, they had a whole bunch of these pictures.
It was really interesting.
The ones that Mondo Rogers had done.
And we were in it.
And he had no idea.
But the thing that impressed me was the enthusiasm that Wardlock showed.
You could just tell that he was a success.
And Jack was very enthused.
And they just said they didn't have a choice but to look at it and think about it.
What else do you remember about the meeting?
But I remember there was lots of people in there.
For some reason, we got two rooms because some of our family was not living in Midland, and they were there together with us.
We'd gone back to... Our office was still there, but I wasn't running.
What do you remember about the meeting?
That's what I remember.
I remember we just had so much fun.
looking at those pictures, all in a lot of excitement.
And we were thinking more about this building than anything else.
So anyhow.
Let me ask you, too.
What did you think about Wardlaw when you first met him?
That was your first encounter with Frank Wardlaw?
He was the most enthusiastic guy.
You've got to have enthusiasm for anything.
He was sincere.
funny, I mean, lovable, and we might have had a few groups up there.
I'm sure you did.
I'm sure you did.
Maybe you say what you thought.
Now, that was my impression that made me really enthusiastic about the project.
Well, I thought that Jack Williams felt the same way as Frank did, and I thought, well, Jack Williams got to be the balance, because here's Frank, all enthusiasm, but somebody else, you know.
And then I guess we decided in two or three days.
Well, I think we decided that night.
But we told him.
Yeah, a little bit later.
That's correct.
If I remember right, Jack Williams told us that to have a great university, you need a great press and a great person, so you've got to have a great library and a great scholarly press.
And I'd say that'd be impressive.
But they left the pictures with us, I believe.
We told them that we'd give them an answer in a day or two if we'd go out to dinner with us.
Did they go?
I didn't remember that, but Haskell said that they stayed.
Haskell wouldn't remember.
He really remembered everything.
We talked to those women.
I believe they said it cost $75,000.
